{
  "buggy_files": ["sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c"],
  "buggy_functions": ["azx_resume", "azx_init_chip"],
  "confidence": 0.75,
  "reasoning": "The bug is in sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c. When azx_rirb_get_response() encounters RIRB timeout during normal operation (e.g., runtime PM power-down sending D3 to codec), it sets chip->polling_mode=1 and eventually chip->single_cmd=1. These flags are NEVER reset during suspend/resume cycles: azx_stop_chip() only clears chip->initialized, and azx_init_chip() does not reset polling_mode or single_cmd. On resume, azx_resume() calls azx_init_chip(chip, 1) which performs a full hardware reset but preserves these stale flags. With polling_mode=1 persisting from a previous session, any new RIRB timeout on the next resume skips the normal poll-count retry mechanism and escalates directly to MSI disable then single_cmd=1. With single_cmd=1, azx_init_cmd_io() is never called in azx_init_chip() (due to 'if (!chip->single_cmd)' guard), so CORB/RIRB stays uninitialized and all codec commands go through the slow single-command path, causing choppy audio. The 'after a few suspends' behavior is explained by state accumulation: polling_mode or poll_count ratchets up across resume cycles until a fatal escalation occurs. The Intel 5 Series/3400 (PCI ID 0x3b56) is assigned AZX_DCAPS_INTEL_PCH which includes AZX_DCAPS_PM_RUNTIME, enabling runtime PM that triggers additional power-down/resume sequences which can cause the RIRB timeouts. The fix should reset chip->polling_mode=0 in azx_resume() or at the start of azx_init_chip() when full_reset=1."
}

